WEBVTT

00:00.830 --> 00:03.370
Raven: Raven's Home
<i>was filmed in front of</i>
<i>a live studio audience.</i>

00:03.370 --> 00:05.420
(buzzing)

00:05.420 --> 00:07.000
Tuna sandwich on rye,

00:07.000 --> 00:09.590
salt and vinegar chips,

00:09.590 --> 00:12.300
and a root beer
to wash it down.

00:12.300 --> 00:15.050
Wow. How'd you know
what I had for lunch?

00:15.050 --> 00:18.180
'Cause you're standing
a little too close.

00:19.640 --> 00:21.230
Sorry.
I'm just...

00:21.230 --> 00:23.690
I'm just learning
so much from you.
I wanna soak it all in.

00:23.690 --> 00:26.190
Yeah, and you're a quick
study to go from house sweeper

00:26.190 --> 00:27.560
to apprentice so quickly.

00:28.070 --> 00:29.400
Here's a breath mint.

00:30.980 --> 00:32.030
So,

00:32.280 --> 00:34.610
Mr. Arthur, do you think I
can start cutting hair soon?

00:34.610 --> 00:37.410
(laughing)

00:37.410 --> 00:39.490
Oh my goodness...

00:39.490 --> 00:41.120
(laughing)

00:41.120 --> 00:42.370
W‐w‐what's so funny?

00:42.370 --> 00:45.170
You! Come on, slow down.

00:45.170 --> 00:47.960
You think Neil Armstrong
hopped in a bouncy house

00:47.960 --> 00:49.250
one day and then said,

00:49.250 --> 00:51.340
"I'm ready to
walk on the moon?"

00:51.340 --> 00:53.130
(laughing)
Come on, man.

00:53.130 --> 00:55.050
What does that have
to do with cutting hair?

00:55.050 --> 00:57.470
Well, it takes years
to be a master cutter!

00:57.470 --> 00:59.890
It's an art form!

00:59.890 --> 01:02.890
If it was easy,
everybody would be doin' it.

01:02.890 --> 01:04.270
But, you said
I was a quick study.

01:04.270 --> 01:06.440
And you need to study some more,

01:06.440 --> 01:08.060
and you need to
get certified.

01:08.560 --> 01:10.230
When did you get
certified, Mr. Arthur?

01:10.230 --> 01:12.990
I was cutting hair
before there was

01:12.990 --> 01:14.950
a board of certification, so...

01:16.200 --> 01:17.990
I'm grandfathered in.

01:17.990 --> 01:20.530
(laughing)

01:22.080 --> 01:23.450
Man, go to work.

01:24.750 --> 01:26.290
<i>‐♪ Hey ♪</i>
<i>‐♪ Yo ♪</i>

01:26.290 --> 01:27.540
<i>♪ Let me tell you somethin' ♪</i>

01:27.540 --> 01:29.080
<i>♪ Had my vision</i>
<i>all worked out ♪</i>

01:29.080 --> 01:31.040
<i>♪ But then life</i>
<i>had other plans ♪</i>

01:31.040 --> 01:32.250
<i>♪ Tell 'em, Rae ♪</i>

01:32.250 --> 01:34.260
<i>♪ It's crazy when things</i>
<i>turn upside down ♪</i>

01:34.260 --> 01:36.970
<i>♪ But ya gotta get up</i>
<i>and take that chance ♪</i>

01:36.970 --> 01:39.340
<i>‐♪ Maybe I'm</i>
<i>just finding my way ♪</i>
<i>‐♪ Learning how to fly ♪</i>

01:39.340 --> 01:41.760
<i>‐♪ Yeah, we're gonna be okay ♪</i>
<i>‐♪ Ya know I got you, right? ♪</i>

01:41.760 --> 01:43.970
<i>♪ It might be wild, but ya</i>
<i>know that we make it work ♪</i>

01:43.970 --> 01:46.440
<i>♪ We're just kids</i>
<i>caught up in a crazy world ♪</i>

01:46.440 --> 01:48.150
‐♪ C'mon! ♪
<i>‐♪ It's</i> Raven's Home ♪

01:48.150 --> 01:50.650
<i>‐♪ We get loud! ♪</i>
<i>‐♪ It's</i> Raven's Home ♪

01:50.650 --> 01:52.150
<i>♪ It's our crowd! ♪</i>

01:52.150 --> 01:54.400
<i>♪ Might be tough,</i>
<i>but together</i>
<i>we make it look good ♪</i>

01:54.400 --> 01:56.700
<i>♪ Down for each other</i>
<i>like family should ♪</i>

01:56.700 --> 01:58.200
<i>♪ It's</i> Raven's Home ♪

01:58.200 --> 01:59.450
<i>♪ When it's tough ♪</i>

01:59.450 --> 02:01.070
<i>♪ It's</i> Raven's Home ♪

02:01.070 --> 02:02.200
<i>♪ We got love ♪</i>

02:02.200 --> 02:04.370
<i>♪ 'Cos no matter the weather,</i>
<i>ya know we gon' shine ♪</i>

02:04.370 --> 02:06.830
<i>♪ There for each other,</i>
<i>ya know it's our time ♪</i>

02:06.830 --> 02:08.040
(Raven laughing)

02:08.040 --> 02:10.330
Yep! That's us.

02:10.330 --> 02:11.420
(laughing)

02:13.250 --> 02:15.920
♪ ♪

02:15.920 --> 02:18.970
Ugh! Why are we always
waiting on Booker?

02:18.970 --> 02:21.090
He always gets
distracted.

02:21.090 --> 02:23.100
Do you see how many
mirrors are in there?

02:24.470 --> 02:26.140
‐What's up, Ramon?
‐Hey, Tess.

02:26.140 --> 02:27.430
'Sup, Nia. What are
you guys doing here?

02:27.430 --> 02:29.230
We're waiting on
a sloth named Booker.

02:29.230 --> 02:32.060
‐(laughing)
‐Yo, Coach Spitz
was on one today.

02:32.060 --> 02:33.570
Why'd he have us
running so many drills?

02:33.570 --> 02:36.990
‐It's like he gets a kick out
of blowing his little whistle.
‐(laughing)

02:36.990 --> 02:39.610
Oh, and speaking of kicks,
those are fresh.

02:39.610 --> 02:41.320
Aw, man, thanks.

02:41.320 --> 02:43.740
I try. I like your haircut.

02:43.740 --> 02:45.740
I try. All right,
well, I gotta go.

02:45.740 --> 02:48.250
‐See you at school tomorrow?
‐Yep. Later.

02:49.830 --> 02:51.170
Ooh!

02:52.460 --> 02:54.040
Someone's got a crush!

02:54.040 --> 02:55.170
What are you talking about?

02:55.170 --> 02:57.050
Oh, don't play
dumb with me, Tess.

02:57.050 --> 02:59.090
Your face is as red as
a new crayon right now.

02:59.550 --> 03:02.430
Ramon and I are just
friends. We're homies.

03:02.430 --> 03:04.850
You mean honeys.

03:05.510 --> 03:07.560
You like him, Tess,
you really like him!

03:07.560 --> 03:09.060
No, stop!
I don't like him!

03:09.060 --> 03:10.730
‐'Sup, y'all?
‐Nothing!

03:10.730 --> 03:13.690
W‐w‐why would you
think something's up?

03:13.690 --> 03:15.070
Gotta go.

03:18.070 --> 03:19.990
Is my breath really that bad?

03:20.900 --> 03:22.070
(breathes, sniffs)

03:24.160 --> 03:27.160
♪ ♪

03:30.830 --> 03:33.290
‐(gasp) Chels, Chels!
‐Hey, hey, hey!

03:33.290 --> 03:36.460
What do you think
about this poster?

03:36.460 --> 03:39.130
"Your Best Dressed Life."
I love it!

03:39.130 --> 03:41.050
I know, right? (scream)

03:41.050 --> 03:42.840
Can you believe we're
almost ready to open?

03:42.840 --> 03:45.180
‐I can't.
‐We got the publicity
in place‐‐

03:45.180 --> 03:46.510
We're expecting
a great turnout‐‐

03:46.510 --> 03:49.020
‐Everything is perfect.
‐It is! It is!

03:49.020 --> 03:51.060
(laughing) Wait.
(clears throat)

03:52.980 --> 03:55.480
Is it? I mean,
we've only life‐styled

03:55.480 --> 03:57.520
one person, like, once.

03:57.520 --> 03:59.690
Chels, we invested

03:59.690 --> 04:01.950
all of our money

04:01.950 --> 04:05.370
into designing a place
and starting a business all...

04:05.370 --> 04:07.990
because of that once.

04:10.080 --> 04:12.660
Yeah, Rae. Once.

04:12.660 --> 04:14.500
I mean, are we really
ready for this?

04:14.500 --> 04:16.380
‐What if we don't
know what we're doing?
‐I don't know.

04:16.380 --> 04:19.250
Is this what impostor
syndrome feels like?

04:19.250 --> 04:20.550
What if we fail?

04:20.550 --> 04:21.670
I don't know, Rae.
I don't know,

04:21.670 --> 04:23.260
but I really can't handle
the pressure, okay?

04:23.260 --> 04:24.340
‐(stirring)
‐I'm freaking out!

04:24.340 --> 04:26.850
Okay, okay, Chels, Chels,
Chels, stop, stop, stop!

04:26.850 --> 04:29.220
Put it down. Okay.

04:29.220 --> 04:32.100
‐Come on, let's‐‐
let's take a breath.
‐Yeah.

04:32.100 --> 04:34.810
(both inhale, exhale)

04:34.810 --> 04:37.270
‐Ah.
‐There you go.
That feels good, right?

04:37.270 --> 04:39.900
(inhale, exhale)

04:40.980 --> 04:42.940
Listen, we cannot
doubt ourselves.

04:42.940 --> 04:45.530
‐The best way to prove
that we're ready‐‐
‐Is leap

04:45.530 --> 04:48.200
and see if we're
given wings to fly!

04:48.200 --> 04:49.620
(laughing)

04:49.620 --> 04:52.120
No, and don't jump 'cause
I'm not gonna catch you.

04:53.910 --> 04:56.080
I'm just saying maybe
we should try out

04:56.080 --> 04:57.540
our services
on each other.

04:57.540 --> 05:00.050
Oh yes! Yes, very good.

05:00.050 --> 05:02.010
Very sensible.
(chuckle)

05:02.010 --> 05:03.970
What exactly do you mean?

05:05.970 --> 05:07.680
You give me a life
coaching session,

05:07.680 --> 05:10.140
and I'll give you
a styling session.

05:10.140 --> 05:11.890
Of course! Yes!
That's a great idea.

05:11.890 --> 05:13.230
I mean, coaching
you will be easy.

05:13.230 --> 05:15.140
‐That right!
‐(laugh)

05:15.730 --> 05:18.020
Mom, Mr. Arthur
is being so unfair.

05:18.020 --> 05:20.400
(baby talk):
Oh baby, what did he
do now to my pumpkin?

05:22.070 --> 05:24.530
Well, Mom, he told me
I wasn't ready to cut hair,

05:24.530 --> 05:26.280
but I've been watching
him work long enough.

05:26.280 --> 05:28.990
‐It's time to put
my skills in action.
‐All right, Booker...

05:30.080 --> 05:31.990
people go to trade school
to become a barber.

05:31.990 --> 05:34.120
You can't just
wake up one morning
with a set of clippers

05:34.120 --> 05:37.000
and roll up on people,
thinking that you
know what's best.

05:37.000 --> 05:39.040
I've been gettin' my
hair cut my whole life.

05:39.040 --> 05:40.750
I think I know what
customers like.

05:41.170 --> 05:43.000
Booker, I need you

05:43.000 --> 05:44.970
to appreciate
this opportunity

05:44.970 --> 05:46.510
that Mr. Arthur
is giving you

05:46.510 --> 05:49.220
and soak up as much
information as you can.

05:50.140 --> 05:53.430
(whoosh)

05:54.390 --> 05:57.770
You've got this.
You can cut every style.

05:58.100 --> 05:59.480
(whoosh)

06:03.150 --> 06:04.690
You know what, Mom?
You're right.

06:04.690 --> 06:07.200
I am going to be happy
with the opportunity.

06:07.200 --> 06:08.570
As you should.

06:08.570 --> 06:09.990
Now, show me those
apprentice skills

06:09.990 --> 06:11.990
and clean up
this kitchen.

06:11.990 --> 06:14.200
♪ ♪

06:14.200 --> 06:17.040
Levi, I can give you

06:17.040 --> 06:18.670
a free haircut.

06:20.040 --> 06:21.040
(shuts drawer)

06:22.040 --> 06:24.090
Um, well...

06:24.090 --> 06:25.630
Come on, Levi!

06:25.630 --> 06:27.340
Take a chance
on your big bro!

06:27.340 --> 06:31.090
I have observed the masters.

06:32.050 --> 06:33.390
You sure you can do this?

06:33.390 --> 06:36.470
I'm sure I can!
And if not,

06:36.470 --> 06:38.270
it‐it will grow back.

06:42.230 --> 06:44.270
Okay, I'll give you a chance.

06:44.270 --> 06:47.280
I've got my fedora
handy just in case.

06:49.360 --> 06:50.410
(sigh)

06:50.410 --> 06:52.820
♪ ♪

06:53.530 --> 06:55.870
All right, Levi,
what do you think?

06:56.790 --> 06:58.620
Wow, this looks great!

06:59.040 --> 07:00.920
Booker, you've got some skills.

07:00.920 --> 07:03.170
See there? I told
Mr. Arthur I was ready.

07:03.170 --> 07:06.090
Maybe one day, you can
start your own barbershop.

07:06.090 --> 07:07.590
Uh, one day?

07:07.590 --> 07:09.470
I gave you
a great cut today.

07:09.470 --> 07:12.180
Okay, well, where would you
start your own barbershop?

07:13.350 --> 07:16.390
‐Our‐our bedroom?
‐Auntie Rae
would never let us.

07:16.390 --> 07:18.100
You're right.
We need a place

07:18.100 --> 07:19.980
where no adults'll
pay attention to us.

07:21.140 --> 07:22.520
Both:
School!

07:25.360 --> 07:27.360
♪ ♪

07:32.030 --> 07:35.120
Nia, I need to ask you
a hypothetical question.

07:35.120 --> 07:37.660
Uh‐oh.
The big words.

07:37.660 --> 07:39.790
Must be serious.
Okay, shoot.

07:39.790 --> 07:42.920
So, say a person did
have a crush on Ramon.

07:42.920 --> 07:44.880
How would that
person go about

07:44.880 --> 07:47.170
taking their relationship
to the next level?

07:47.170 --> 07:49.010
Hypothetically
speaking, of course.

07:49.010 --> 07:50.720
Oh, Tess, I knew it,
I knew it.

07:50.720 --> 07:52.300
‐Oh, you guys
would be so cute...
‐Nia, stop!

07:53.340 --> 07:55.760
‐Hey, see you in class.
‐You know it!

07:55.760 --> 07:56.970
Hey, Nia.

07:58.060 --> 08:00.850
Tess! What was that?
Why didn't you say something?

08:00.850 --> 08:03.350
I did.
I said, "you know it."

08:05.610 --> 08:07.020
That's not what I meant.

08:07.020 --> 08:10.070
Come on, Nia.
The last time
I was crushing on a guy,

08:10.070 --> 08:11.440
he blocked my shot.

08:12.070 --> 08:14.070
Rejection is painful.

08:15.200 --> 08:17.370
Okay, well, why
don't I find out

08:17.370 --> 08:20.750
if he likes you by
doing what I do best.

08:20.750 --> 08:23.000
‐Homework.
‐On Ramon?

08:23.000 --> 08:26.040
Now, that's a class
I'd like to take.

08:26.040 --> 08:27.290
(laughing)

08:27.290 --> 08:30.300
♪ ♪

08:31.260 --> 08:33.010
(bell ringing)

08:35.470 --> 08:38.050
Now, now there it is!
Ha, ha!

08:38.050 --> 08:40.060
Just a quick raid of
the janitor's closet

08:40.060 --> 08:43.060
and Booker's Bathroom Cuts
is open for business.

08:43.060 --> 08:45.940
Hey, do you think he'll notice
his furniture's missing?

08:45.940 --> 08:48.570
Pssh. Look at how
clean this place is!

08:48.570 --> 08:50.150
He's not gonna be back
for another month,

08:50.150 --> 08:52.150
so for
the next 30 days,

08:52.150 --> 08:55.740
this place belongs
to Booker Baxter,

08:55.740 --> 08:58.200
‐barber.
‐(toilet flush)

08:59.240 --> 09:00.950
Hoo!

09:01.490 --> 09:03.160
Good thing
I brought the spray!

09:04.160 --> 09:05.540
‐Ew!
‐Okay, okay!

09:07.170 --> 09:09.710
And I'm ready to sweep.
Oh, selfie!

09:09.710 --> 09:11.380
‐Tag me!
‐(shutter snap)

09:11.380 --> 09:12.550
Fantastic.

09:13.590 --> 09:16.970
Hey, Curtis! My man!
It's your lucky day.

09:18.010 --> 09:19.180
What are you guys doing?

09:19.970 --> 09:23.100
‐Would you like a haircut?
‐Uh, I don't think so?

09:23.100 --> 09:25.140
I'm just here to
use the bathroom.

09:25.140 --> 09:26.600
Well, the bathroom's free!

09:26.600 --> 09:28.520
So is this haircut
I'm offering, by the way.

09:28.520 --> 09:31.780
I'll just clean up your edges!
I'm the best barber in school.

09:31.780 --> 09:33.780
He's the only
barber in school.

09:34.610 --> 09:37.110
♪ ♪

09:37.110 --> 09:39.450
Chels, I am so excited
we're doing this.

09:39.450 --> 09:41.450
‐Are you ready? Okay.
‐Yeah, yeah, yeah!

09:43.370 --> 09:45.080
‐Hello, Ms. Grayson.
‐Hello.

09:45.080 --> 09:47.960
I have brought you
a few options

09:47.960 --> 09:50.290
to add some oomph
to your style.

09:50.290 --> 09:53.170
(English accent):
Ooh! Well, I love
a little oomph!

09:53.170 --> 09:55.130
(laughter)

09:55.130 --> 09:57.430
These are...
these are nice.

09:57.430 --> 10:00.800
I know you normally go with
the romantic, flowy top look,

10:00.800 --> 10:03.060
‐blowing in the wind.
‐Yes. (giggle)

10:03.060 --> 10:04.520
But I think that
you could benefit

10:04.520 --> 10:07.480
from a real
structured boss look.

10:07.480 --> 10:10.110
‐O... kay.
‐Yeah.

10:10.110 --> 10:12.110
Lemme see,
turn around. Oh yes.

10:13.020 --> 10:15.030
Yes. (muttering)

10:16.530 --> 10:17.990
Oh.

10:18.990 --> 10:21.160
I don't know, Rae.
I don't know
if this really feels

10:21.160 --> 10:23.030
like, like me, you know?

10:23.030 --> 10:25.040
Oh, that's because it's not.

10:25.040 --> 10:26.410
It's better! (laugh)

10:29.170 --> 10:31.130
‐What?
‐Oh.

10:31.130 --> 10:34.300
Well, our company's name is
Your Best Dressed Life, so...

10:34.300 --> 10:36.920
this is your best.

10:40.550 --> 10:43.050
And in working towards
your best self,

10:43.050 --> 10:45.060
you‐you really need
to be more aware of

10:45.060 --> 10:46.680
how your words
impact others.

10:46.680 --> 10:49.140
Oh, I am very aware
of what I say.

10:51.190 --> 10:53.020
For example (clears throat),

10:53.020 --> 10:56.650
when you say to someone
it's not you, it's better,

10:56.650 --> 10:58.860
(laugh) can you see how

10:58.860 --> 11:01.780
that might make a person
feel badly about themselves?

11:01.780 --> 11:04.780
I'm not in charge of feels,
Chels. That's you.

11:06.450 --> 11:07.950
And another thing
(clears throat),

11:07.950 --> 11:11.250
maybe don't yell
so much, you know?

11:11.250 --> 11:14.170
I don't yell.
I speak in a loud tone.

11:14.170 --> 11:16.170
‐Oh.
‐It's called passion.

11:18.210 --> 11:20.930
Okay.
Is passion code for

11:20.930 --> 11:23.600
abrasive and belligerent?

11:24.640 --> 11:27.430
When I'm being belligerent,
you gon' know.

11:27.430 --> 11:29.100
You ever heard
the expression,

11:29.100 --> 11:31.560
"You catch more flies
with honey than
you do with vinegar?"

11:32.190 --> 11:34.610
You ever heard the expression,
"Hold my earrings?"

11:36.190 --> 11:39.280
♪ ♪

11:39.280 --> 11:41.780
Mm, I look great.

11:43.070 --> 11:45.030
‐Mm.
‐Yes, you do!

11:48.120 --> 11:49.290
You're as good as the pros.

11:49.290 --> 11:51.870
‐At zero the price.
‐Tell your friends

11:51.870 --> 11:53.330
they can book
appointments with me,

11:53.330 --> 11:55.790
but walk‐ins are welcome.

11:55.790 --> 11:58.710
Look, he should be coming
right about... now.

11:59.090 --> 12:01.220
You know what to do.
Figure out who he likes,

12:01.220 --> 12:02.930
but don't tell
him I like him.

12:02.930 --> 12:05.550
Copy. And don't worry, Tess.
I'll get all the tea, all right?

12:09.930 --> 12:11.430
Hey, Ramon!
Come here!

12:12.890 --> 12:14.190
Hey, what's up, Nia?

12:14.190 --> 12:16.110
So, I figured you'd be
passing by on your way

12:16.110 --> 12:17.270
from Spanish to
science class.

12:17.270 --> 12:19.360
Oh, uh, you know my schedule?

12:19.360 --> 12:21.440
‐Yeah. I'm very observant.
‐Oh.

12:21.440 --> 12:23.910
So, uh, have you
finished reading
<i>A Raisin in the Sun</i> yet?

12:23.910 --> 12:26.240
Uh, yeah. Wait, you're
not in my English class.

12:26.240 --> 12:29.580
No, but I am a student
of fine literature.

12:29.580 --> 12:31.700
‐Uh, well, I really
like the play.
‐What else

12:31.700 --> 12:33.710
do you like, Ramon?
Tell me more.

12:33.710 --> 12:35.080
‐Uh‐‐
‐Your class is this way.

12:36.210 --> 12:39.550
I said, Teach, you can't bring
a live peacock to school‐‐

12:39.550 --> 12:40.340
So!

12:42.050 --> 12:43.680
What kind of
girls do you like?

12:44.220 --> 12:45.640
Did you see I was
talking to somebody?

12:45.970 --> 12:48.430
Eh, not anymore.
Now, you're talking to me.

12:48.430 --> 12:49.810
Don't you like
talking to me?

12:49.810 --> 12:51.270
Uh, sure.

12:51.270 --> 12:53.600
So, Ramon, you never
answered my question.

12:53.600 --> 12:56.100
‐What kind of girls
do you like?
‐Uh, nice.

12:56.100 --> 12:57.980
Like, laid back.

12:58.730 --> 13:00.070
Cool, cool,
cool, cool, cool.

13:00.070 --> 13:02.030
So, uh,
girls with dark hair

13:02.030 --> 13:04.650
whose eyes light up in the sun,
who know what they want?

13:04.650 --> 13:06.450
Uh, yeah.
Yeah, I like that.

13:06.450 --> 13:08.950
Nice.
Girls who are swaggy,
smart, and talented,

13:08.950 --> 13:10.660
like a certain girl
at this school?

13:10.660 --> 13:13.080
‐Um...
‐(bell rings)

13:13.080 --> 13:14.080
I better get to class.

13:14.870 --> 13:17.420
Oh, you're punctual!
I see, Ramon!

13:17.420 --> 13:19.840
We'll talk more after class!

13:19.840 --> 13:22.840
♪ ♪

13:22.840 --> 13:24.590
Well, I'm Chelsea,
and even though

13:24.590 --> 13:27.090
I'm a hot mess,
I still think I can
help other people!

13:27.090 --> 13:28.640
(gasp)

13:28.640 --> 13:30.970
Okay, well, I'm Raven, huh?
And‐and I wear

13:30.970 --> 13:33.770
(imitating):
bold colors
and haute couture

13:33.770 --> 13:37.350
so everyone will pay
attention to me‐‐
me, me, me!

13:37.350 --> 13:39.110
‐Well‐‐ well‐‐
‐Me! Me!

13:42.360 --> 13:45.650
Well, I'm Chelsea,
and I have to remind everyone

13:45.650 --> 13:48.320
that I was an interpretive
dance major!

13:49.370 --> 13:51.700
Ooh! Oh, I'm Raven,

13:51.700 --> 13:53.450
and I have to tell everyone

13:53.450 --> 13:56.210
that I have visions!
I have visions!

13:59.630 --> 14:02.090
Ooh! But, but wait!

14:02.090 --> 14:03.670
My visions are
never correct,

14:03.670 --> 14:06.130
but I still have them!

14:06.130 --> 14:09.510
Well, I'm Chelsea, and I sing
everything like it's opera!

14:09.510 --> 14:12.510
(singing notes
higher and higher)

14:13.260 --> 14:14.970
(high pitched):
This is a pop song,

14:14.970 --> 14:17.140
but I don't sing it like that!

14:17.140 --> 14:20.150
(holds high note)

14:20.150 --> 14:23.110
♪ ♪

14:24.900 --> 14:27.200
Man, the word
is out, Levi.

14:27.200 --> 14:29.570
Yep, we have successfully
launched a new business.

14:30.870 --> 14:32.620
(toilet flush)

14:32.620 --> 14:34.620
‐Come on.
‐(spraying)

14:36.950 --> 14:39.790
You know, thanks for coming.
We appreciate your business.

14:41.710 --> 14:43.090
Okay.

14:44.300 --> 14:45.300
(clears throat)

14:46.380 --> 14:49.590
So, would you, uh,

14:49.590 --> 14:51.300
would you like an edge up?

14:53.050 --> 14:55.010
Oh. Are you sure?

14:55.010 --> 14:58.020
'Cause edge ups are
kinda my specialty.

14:58.020 --> 14:59.060
I mean,

14:59.060 --> 15:01.060
look at Levi.

15:01.060 --> 15:02.520
Look at Curtis.

15:02.520 --> 15:03.690
You got this.

15:03.690 --> 15:05.570
You can cut every style.

15:06.070 --> 15:08.440
You know what, Curtis?
You're right.

15:08.950 --> 15:11.990
You know, I think it's time
I expand my repertoire.

15:11.990 --> 15:13.120
(buzzing)

15:13.120 --> 15:15.120
(clears throat)
All right, let's see.

15:17.330 --> 15:20.290
‐(clippers sputter)
‐Uh, uh, uh, uh, uh...

15:21.080 --> 15:22.630
I can fix that!
I can fix that.

15:23.840 --> 15:25.840
(buzzing)

15:26.550 --> 15:27.960
‐(clippers sputter)
‐Mm!

15:29.920 --> 15:30.970
Uh, uh...

15:31.970 --> 15:33.850
Uh, you know what?

15:33.850 --> 15:36.060
Th‐this one's on the house.

15:36.510 --> 15:37.930
(buzzing)

15:38.600 --> 15:40.020
All right. (clears throat)

15:42.190 --> 15:43.940
‐(clippers sputter)
‐(thud)

15:48.110 --> 15:50.070
Th‐that's kind of
a taper fade, right?

15:56.030 --> 15:58.540
Um, this is on the house.

15:58.540 --> 15:59.830
♪ ♪

15:59.830 --> 16:01.500
(buzzing)

16:01.500 --> 16:02.750
(clippers sputter)

16:07.550 --> 16:10.550
The good news is
I cleaned up your fro.

16:10.550 --> 16:13.930
The better news is
it's on the house.

16:14.720 --> 16:16.720
(flush)

16:18.930 --> 16:21.350
♪ ♪

16:24.850 --> 16:26.400
‐(bang)
‐Whoa.

16:26.400 --> 16:28.150
So, what's
more important,

16:28.400 --> 16:31.240
swag or smarts?
But, you know what?
Why choose?

16:31.240 --> 16:33.740
Okay, listen, Nia,
I think you're cool,

16:33.740 --> 16:35.160
um, but you're not
really my type.

16:36.120 --> 16:37.580
Excuse me?

16:37.580 --> 16:38.950
I'm everybody's type.

16:40.200 --> 16:42.120
(nervous laugh)
Look, you're really nice,

16:42.120 --> 16:44.330
but I think it's best
if we stay friends.

16:44.330 --> 16:47.040
‐Wait, no,
I am not trying to‐‐
‐Wait, Ramon!

16:47.040 --> 16:49.300
Nia's not
interested in you.

16:49.300 --> 16:51.920
Then, why was she asking
me all these questions

16:51.920 --> 16:53.380
and memorizing my schedule?

16:54.130 --> 16:57.510
She was... she was
actually asking for me.

16:58.550 --> 17:00.140
Because I like you.

17:01.140 --> 17:03.850
And she knows
everyone's schedule.

17:03.850 --> 17:05.730
You ever heard of
research, brah?

17:08.980 --> 17:11.360
Wait, Tess, you like me?

17:11.360 --> 17:12.990
Yeah.

17:12.990 --> 17:16.110
She was asking if you
like swaggy girls.

17:16.110 --> 17:17.740
‐I'm all swag.
‐Yeah.

17:17.740 --> 17:19.950
Yeah, you are,
and you're smart,

17:19.950 --> 17:21.450
and you're pretty and funny.

17:21.450 --> 17:22.950
Aw...

17:22.950 --> 17:24.960
You don't have to
say all those things,

17:24.960 --> 17:26.960
but please continue.

17:27.670 --> 17:30.130
Hey, um,
I wanna ask you out,

17:30.130 --> 17:31.880
but I don't wanna
hurt Nia's feelings.

17:31.880 --> 17:33.970
I'm not interested,
all right?!

17:35.260 --> 17:36.880
So, you were saying...

17:37.260 --> 17:40.220
I was saying, wanna
hang out some time?

17:41.560 --> 17:42.850
For sure.

17:42.850 --> 17:45.890
♪ ♪

17:51.980 --> 17:54.490
Boy, I haven't caught a whiff
of your breath all day.

17:54.490 --> 17:55.820
What's going on with you?

17:56.070 --> 17:59.370
Nothing, sir, just,
uh, doing the job
you hired me for.

17:59.370 --> 18:01.910
Well, I guess there's
a first time for everything.

18:01.910 --> 18:03.700
Just last week, I tried that

18:03.700 --> 18:06.580
new fax machine gizmo.

18:09.960 --> 18:12.130
Whoa, whoa!

18:14.010 --> 18:15.970
What is going on here?

18:17.050 --> 18:18.930
Were the drones
flying too low?

18:20.390 --> 18:23.060
I'm telling you,
these drones are
gonna be the end of us.

18:23.060 --> 18:25.640
Back in my day,
if you wanted to see
something high,

18:25.640 --> 18:27.270
you'd climb a tree.

18:27.270 --> 18:29.150
But, hey, I'm not mad.

18:29.520 --> 18:32.190
We haven't been this busy
since the Jheri Curl dried up.

18:32.190 --> 18:34.150
(laughing)

18:36.860 --> 18:39.110
Who messed up your
heads like this?

18:44.160 --> 18:47.120
♪ ♪

18:48.040 --> 18:50.630
All right. Tess is in
my room getting ready.

18:50.630 --> 18:52.170
Her date is gonna come
up here and pick her up.

18:52.170 --> 18:54.090
Do you guys have any
last‐minute advice

18:54.090 --> 18:55.670
or style tips that
you can give her?

18:55.670 --> 18:57.550
Uh, yeah, yeah,
lemme just

18:57.550 --> 19:00.180
yell it back at her!
Hey, Tess!

19:02.010 --> 19:04.930
Blue really makes
your eyes pop!

19:05.930 --> 19:07.730
Tess:
Thank you!

19:07.730 --> 19:09.140
Oh hey, Tess,
I'm so sorry

19:09.140 --> 19:11.150
I can't help you
with your date, honey!

19:11.150 --> 19:13.520
I'm not my best self, so...

19:14.980 --> 19:17.610
Tess:
Uh, can‐can you send
Nia back here?

19:18.400 --> 19:20.070
All right, I don't know
what's going on
with you two,

19:20.070 --> 19:22.410
but please don't be this
way when her date arrives.

19:22.410 --> 19:23.950
(doorbell rings)

19:23.950 --> 19:25.240
I'm gonna go get Tess.

19:30.040 --> 19:31.370
‐Oh, hi, Ramon!
‐Hi, Ramon!

19:31.370 --> 19:33.330
‐Hi.
‐Come on in, honey.
Come in.

19:33.330 --> 19:35.250
Listen, you are going
on a date with a very

19:35.250 --> 19:36.960
confident young lady,
all right?

19:36.960 --> 19:38.760
You need to speak
with more bravado!

19:38.760 --> 19:41.180
‐Huh? Yeah!
‐Uh‐‐ hey!

19:41.180 --> 19:43.220
‐Okay.
‐Good evening, Miss...

19:43.220 --> 19:44.550
Tess' neighbor.

19:44.550 --> 19:47.600
Huh, okay! Good job!
Good evening,
good evening, yes.

19:47.600 --> 19:49.600
‐Yes, good.
‐Oh, that looks great.

19:49.600 --> 19:51.640
Is this your favorite shirt
or is it a new shirt?

19:51.640 --> 19:54.060
‐Uh, favorite shirt.
‐Good. Always good
to stay comfortable,

19:54.060 --> 19:55.820
but not too
comfortable, all right?

19:55.820 --> 19:57.150
Lemme guess.
You're Nia's mom?

19:57.150 --> 19:59.820
‐Oh yes, yes, yes.
There we go.
‐Well...

19:59.820 --> 20:01.650
Hey, Ramon.

20:01.650 --> 20:03.490
Tess!

20:03.490 --> 20:05.660
Wow, you look great.

20:05.660 --> 20:06.870
Um, are you ready to go?

20:07.120 --> 20:08.700
Yeah.

20:08.700 --> 20:10.790
‐Thanks for everything, bestie.
‐Have fun.

20:15.880 --> 20:17.040
Oh, thank you for the advice,

20:17.040 --> 20:18.920
and fashion tip,

20:18.920 --> 20:21.170
Miss neighbor ladies.

20:23.970 --> 20:25.720
I love love.

20:25.720 --> 20:27.720
Raven/Chelsea:
Me, too. (chuckling)

20:30.060 --> 20:31.480
Rae,

20:31.480 --> 20:33.270
look, I‐I'm sorry

20:33.270 --> 20:35.190
if I offended
you earlier.

20:35.190 --> 20:37.190
I love that you're...

20:37.190 --> 20:39.610
passionate about life.

20:39.610 --> 20:40.780
I'm sorry, too, Chels.

20:40.780 --> 20:43.530
‐You really did give
me some great advice.
‐Oh!

20:43.530 --> 20:46.910
And I think that
our business is...
is gonna be okay.

20:46.910 --> 20:49.290
Of course it is.
It's gonna be
better than okay.

20:49.290 --> 20:51.080
You know why?

20:51.080 --> 20:53.620
Because we have
each other. (laugh)

20:53.620 --> 20:55.420
‐I love you.
‐I love you.

20:55.420 --> 20:56.630
(both muttering)

20:56.630 --> 20:58.000
Oh. No!

20:58.420 --> 21:00.920
I think this is
too much love.

21:00.920 --> 21:03.880
♪ ♪

21:06.930 --> 21:08.680
Gimme that.

21:11.770 --> 21:13.020
Well, Book,
I guess I owe you.

21:13.930 --> 21:15.600
Um, for what?

21:15.600 --> 21:17.190
For all the new
customers you brought in

21:17.190 --> 21:19.440
because you
screwed up their heads.

21:20.980 --> 21:22.740
Yeah, well...

21:22.740 --> 21:25.110
You need to give those
people their money back.

21:25.360 --> 21:26.820
I didn't charge them.

21:26.820 --> 21:27.990
Good.

21:28.490 --> 21:30.700
You understand why I said
you're not ready to be a barber?

21:31.910 --> 21:34.160
‐I guess.
‐I wasn't saying no

21:34.160 --> 21:36.000
for the sake of saying no.
As an apprentice,

21:36.000 --> 21:39.080
your job is to
watch and learn.

21:39.080 --> 21:41.460
And I have been. A lot.

21:41.460 --> 21:43.510
And when you're ready,

21:43.510 --> 21:46.720
I'll be happy to hand you
your own set of clippers.

21:46.720 --> 21:49.800
But, you gotta crawl
before you walk.

21:50.430 --> 21:51.430
I understand.

21:52.220 --> 21:54.350
Cheeseburger with onion rings,

21:54.350 --> 21:57.350
coleslaw, sweet potato fries.

21:59.100 --> 22:00.310
That's not what
I had for lunch.

22:00.310 --> 22:01.650
No, somebody threw
that in the trash.

22:03.070 --> 22:05.150
Go take those cans out back.

22:05.900 --> 22:07.110
‐Yes, sir.
‐Yeah.

22:07.110 --> 22:10.120
♪ ♪

22:11.990 --> 22:14.290
‐All right, son, now take
it easy. Doin' good.
‐(buzzing)

22:14.290 --> 22:17.160
‐(sigh)
‐Slow and steady wins the race.

22:17.160 --> 22:20.130
(scoff) Steady being
the operative word.

22:21.540 --> 22:23.920
Leave him alone, Levi!
He's trying to concentrate!

22:23.920 --> 22:27.090
Well then, maybe you
two should be quiet.

22:28.220 --> 22:30.680
Come on, Booker.
Fade it, Booker, fade it‐‐
Ow!

22:30.680 --> 22:32.680
That is my baby!

22:33.600 --> 22:36.770
All right.
What do you guys think?

22:36.770 --> 22:38.350
Not bad,
young blood.

22:39.560 --> 22:42.770
In a few years,
you might be ready
for a human subject.

22:42.770 --> 22:45.650
‐A few years?
‐Yeah!

22:45.650 --> 22:48.110
I started on
a bonsai tree,

22:48.110 --> 22:51.120
then a poodle,
then moved up to an alpaca.

22:52.240 --> 22:53.240
That's how you train.

22:55.080 --> 22:57.040
Mr. Arthur, I wanna
thank you so much

22:57.040 --> 22:58.580
for being a great
influence on Booker.

22:58.580 --> 23:00.040
Oh, you don't have to thank me.

23:00.040 --> 23:01.380
That's what I'm supposed to do.

23:01.920 --> 23:04.250
I know it's probably
hard to believe, but, uh,

23:04.250 --> 23:06.880
‐I used to be a knucklehead.
‐(gasp) No!

23:06.880 --> 23:09.510
‐Mm‐hmm. Yeah. Yeah.
‐No. No!

23:09.510 --> 23:11.010
(laughter)

23:11.010 --> 23:12.720
Well, I know it's hard to
believe, but I used to be

23:12.720 --> 23:14.260
a little bit of
a knucklehead myself.

23:14.260 --> 23:16.890
Oh. Oh, I...

23:17.560 --> 23:18.850
I believe it.

23:19.440 --> 23:21.940
♪ ♪
